  <h2 id="faqs">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is SafetyWing Nomad Insurance real health insurance?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        No. Nomad Insurance is travel medical insurance—it covers emergencies and acute illness while traveling. It doesn't cover routine care, checkups, pre-existing conditions, mental health, or maternity. If you need actual health insurance, you need Remote Health or a different provider. This is the most common misunderstanding about SafetyWing.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I use Nomad Insurance as a US citizen in the US?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Only for 30 days per 90-day period. Nomad Insurance is designed for travel outside your home country. US citizens can use it abroad and during short home visits, but it's not a replacement for US health insurance. If you spend significant time in the US, consider Aetna or GeoBlue instead.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if I get sick with a pre-existing condition?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Nomad Insurance: Not covered, period. Remote Health: Covered after a 24-month waiting period. If you have significant pre-existing conditions and need coverage sooner, Allianz Care offers moratorium underwriting where conditions can be covered after 2 years of no symptoms/treatment—potentially faster than waiting 24 months.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does the subscription model work?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Nomad Insurance auto-renews every 4 weeks. You can cancel anytime through your dashboard, and coverage ends at the end of your current paid period. No cancellation fees, no penalties. You can also pause and restart coverage as needed—useful if you're returning to your home country for an extended period.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is $250,000 maximum coverage enough?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        It depends where you are. For most countries, $250K covers even serious emergencies. However, a major hospitalization in the US can exceed $250K—especially cardiac events, cancer treatment, or ICU stays. If you'll be in the US, the coverage limit is a real risk. Consider higher-limit options like IMG ($5M) or Cigna ($2M+) for US exposure.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How do claims and reimbursements work?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        For most claims: pay upfront, save receipts, submit through the online portal, receive reimbursement in 10-30 days via direct deposit or PayPal. For hospitalizations over $1,000: call the assistance line first, they coordinate direct billing with the hospital. Direct billing is limited compared to traditional insurers—expect to handle most claims as reimbursements.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="final-verdict">Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    SafetyWing solved a real problem: making travel insurance simple, flexible, and affordable for the modern nomad. Their subscription model—no annual commitments, instant signup, cancel anytime—is genuinely better than traditional travel insurance.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Nomad Insurance</strong> is excellent value for what it is: emergency coverage for healthy travelers. At $45/month for ages under 40, it's a quarter the cost of comprehensive health insurance. If you're young, healthy, moving between countries, and just need catastrophic protection, Nomad Insurance makes sense.
  </p>
  <p>
    But understand the limitations. <strong>Nomad Insurance is not health insurance</strong>. It doesn't cover routine care, pre-existing conditions, mental health, or maternity. The $250K maximum can be insufficient for serious US medical events. If you need actual health coverage—not just emergency backup—look at Remote Health or traditional insurers like Cigna, Allianz, or IMG.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Remote Health</strong> fills the gap for expats who need comprehensive coverage but like SafetyWing's approach. It costs 3-5x more than Nomad Insurance because it's actual health insurance. It's competitive with other comprehensive options, though you may find better direct billing networks and customer service with established insurers.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Bottom line:</strong> SafetyWing is a great fit for young, healthy nomads who need flexible emergency coverage. It's not the right fit if you have health conditions, need comprehensive coverage, or want premium customer service. Know what you're buying, and SafetyWing delivers exactly what it promises.
  </p>

